pr_title: Load dataset without reading its generation code
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 473135081, 'comment_body': 'We should not direct import members.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 19, 15, 54, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 473138648, 'comment_body': "Let's try to avoid duplication code with `tfds.load`. Let's also try to better layer this feature in smaller independent pieces.

I would rename this `builder_from_directory(name, *, data_dir)` and remove all the `as_dataset` related things.

1. (this PR) Add `builder_from_directory(builder_dir: str) -> tfds.core.DatasetBuilder`

```python
builder = tfds.core.builder_from_directory('path/to/my_dataset/config/1.0.0')
ds = builder.as_dataset(split='train')
```

2. Add a `find_builder_dir(dataset_name: str, *, data_dir: str) -> builder_dir`

```python
find_builder_dir('my_dataset/config:1.2.0', data_dir='~/tensorflow_datasets/') == '~/tensorflow_datasets/my_dataset/1.2.0'

# If the version is not specified, return the last available version
find_builder_dir('my_dataset', data_dir='~/tensorflow_datasets/') == '~/tensorflow_datasets/my_dataset/config/1.2.0'

# If the dataset, config or version is not found, return None
find_builder_dir('my_dataset/config:1.3.0', data_dir='~/tensorflow_datasets/') == None
```

The main issue here will be to infer the default config when not specified: `dataset` -> `dataset/default_config:x.y.z`. Let's not have this use case for now, we could fix it later.

3. Integrate this with `tfds.load`.

```python
# If find_builder_dir found something, return it, otherwise load from the source code
ds = tfds.load('mnist')
```

", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 7, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470517262, 'comment_body': 'No problem ðŸ™‚
Will work on something else in the meantime.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 9, 31, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vijayphoenix', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 470597844, 'comment_body': "As I started looking into this, it seems that the reason why the `SplitInfo` is complicated was because the way `DatasetInfo` was written.

Currently, we need to keep `info.splits` and `info._info_proto` in sync, so updating `info.splits` require to notify `info._info_proto`. This makes the code hard to follow.
It's my fault for implementing this like that.

We should update `DatasetInfo` to be a `dataclasses.dataclass(frozen=True)`, and rather than using the proto as ground truth, use the DatasetInfo attributes. So we can update `info.splits` without having to update the proto.

So 
```py
class DatasetInfo:
  ...

  @property
  def as_proto(self):
    return self._info_proto

  @property
  def name(self):
    return self.as_proto.name
```
would become:
```py
@dataclasses.dataclass(frozen=True)
class DatasetInfo:
  ...

  name: str

  @property
  def as_proto(self):
    return dataset_info_pb2.DatasetInfo(
        name=self.name,
    )
```

There wouldn't be `_info_proto `, and `as_proto` would only be called when saving in `write_to_directory`, instead of for every attributes

Some implementations details:
* With `(frozen=True)`, because info is mutable, we can use `object.__setattr__(self, 'name', value)` when we need to update dataset info, like inside `read_from_directory`.
* The current __init__ would be changed as post_init to cleanup the arguments:


```py
@dataclasses.dataclass(frozen=True)
class _DatasetInfo:
  
  def __post_init__(self):
    object.__setattr__(self, 'version', self.builder.version)
    if self.description:
      object.__setattr__(self, 'description', utils.dedent(self.description))
```

You can look into this if you want but it's possible that I missed something again which would make this more complicated than expected.
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 14, 12, 37, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Support datasets in folders with checksums & fake_data
pr_body:
Related to https://github.com/tensorflow/datasets/issues/2139

Required directory structure for datasets outside TFDS:
```
path/to/dataset/
    my_dataset.py
    my_dataset_test.py
    my_dataset.txt
    fake_examples/
 ```

TODO:
- [ ] Update [Define the dataset outside TFDS](https://www.tensorflow.org/datasets/add_dataset#define_the_dataset_outside_tfds) doc.
- [ ] Remove unnecessary flags in `download_and_prepare` script
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 448083858, 'comment_body': "I don't think we should add a new flag.
TFDS should automatically detect whether the checksums,... are defined, then fallback to default values otherwise.
", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 1, 2, 40, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 448084726, 'comment_body': 'Adding a checksums dir may have a significant overhead if many datasets are loaded at the same time. Instead, we should update `download_and_prepare` or `DownloadManager` to check whether some `checksums.tsv` is present locally, and load checksums from this file if so. Otherwise, fallback to legacy checksums.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 1, 2, 44, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451019406, 'comment_body': "This doesn't seems to be the right place to load the checksums. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 7, 17, 24, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451027040, 'comment_body': '`_get_url_infos` should be renamed `get_url_infos` if it is now part of the public API.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 7, 17, 26, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 452508882, 'comment_body': 'One line docstring and typing annotations ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 21, 47, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 452509136, 'comment_body': 'This will raise an error if this if checksums_path is None', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 21, 47, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 452509429, 'comment_body': '`DATASET_CLASS.code_dir()`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 21, 48, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 452591158, 'comment_body': "Rather than inheriting from an existing dataset, I think it's best to write a small dataset from scratch (similar to the one in `test_utils.py`).

pr_title: Renaming files on windows fails sometimes
pr_body:
This bug is not related to `tf.io.gfile.rename` as `os.rename` also fails to rename files. This bug probably occurs because the `rename` function fails to acquire a `lock`. Related to https://github.com/tensorflow/datasets/issues/1911#issuecomment-616219946
See pytest results

``` PS C:\Users\VIJAY\Desktop\GitHub_Repos\datasets> python .\tensorflow_datasets\image_classification\horses_or_humans_test.py Running tests under Python 3.7.6: C:\ProgramData\Miniconda3\python.exe [ RUN ] HorsesOrHumansTest.test_baseclass [ OK ] HorsesOrHumansTest.test_baseclass [ RUN ] HorsesOrHumansTest.test_download_and_prepare_as_dataset Total configs: 0 I0420 02:50:07.489775 8064 dataset_builder.py:333] Generating dataset horses_or_humans (C:\Users\VIJAY\AppData\Local\Temp\horses_or_humans_testv9ls7ywi\tmp81u89vgv\horses_or_humans\3.0.0) I0420 02:50:07.489775 8064 dataset_builder.py:333] Generating dataset horses_or_humans (C:\Users\VIJAY\AppData\Local\Temp\horses_or_humans_testv9ls7ywi\tmp81u89vgv\horses_or_humans\3.0.0) Downloading and preparing dataset horses_or_humans/3.0.0 (download: Unknown size, generated: Unknown size, total: Unknown size) to C:\Users\VIJAY\AppData\Local\Temp\horses_or_humans_testv9ls7ywi\tmp81u89vgv\horses_or_humans\3.0.0... I0420 02:50:07.567562 8064 dataset_builder.py:924] Generating split train I0420 02:50:07.567562 8064 dataset_builder.py:924] Generating split train Shuffling and writing examples to C:\Users\VIJAY\AppData\Local\Temp\horses_or_humans_testv9ls7ywi\tmp81u89vgv\horses_or_humans\3.0.0.incompleteWO0GI5\horses_or_humans-train.tfrecord 0%| | 0/2 [00:00 ```

pr_body:
Fix #1707
When we use the following command
```
python -m tensorflow_datasets.scripts.download_and_prepare --datasets=scientific_papers:1.1.0
```
the `download_and_prepare` script should make the following `builder`
```
tfds.builder("scientific_papers:1.1.0",
              data_dir=FLAGS.data_dir,
              config=config,
              **version_kwarg))
```
but previously it made
```
tfds.builder("scientific_papers",
              data_dir=FLAGS.data_dir,
              config=config,
              **version_kwarg))
```
So `scientific_papers:1.1.1` was downloaded instead of `scientific_papers:1.1.0`.

pr_body:
# Add Dataset

* Dataset Name: affNIST
* Issue Reference: #1424 
* `dataset_info.json`: [Gist](https://gist.github.com/vijayphoenix/2fe04278e16349f291b4fcda87d0b6ad)

## Description
Added `affNIST` dataset.
The affNIST dataset is based on the well-known MNIST dataset. It is made by taking images from MNIST and applying various reasonable affine transformations to them.
  
## Checklist
* [x] Address all TODO's
* [x] Add alphabetized import to subdirectory's `__init__.py`
* [x] Run `download_and_prepare` successfully
* [x] Add checksums file
* [x] Properly cite in `BibTeX` format
* [x] Add passing test(s)
* [x] Add test data
* [x] Add data generation script (if applicable)
* [x] Lint code

[{'comment_id': 417522108, 'comment_body': 'What are you expecting this to be used for ?
I think documentations issues could go into other category (bug report or feature request).
Should we improve the other templates documentation instead ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 29, 18, 25, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 417524594, 'comment_body': 'Rather than naming some symbols which may be obscure for new contributors, I would instead only add a single item with a link to the doc.

* [ ] If using additional dependencies (e.g. `nltk`), use [lazy_imports](https://www.tensorflow.org/datasets/add_dataset#extra_dependencies)
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 29, 18, 29, 51, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Conchylicultor', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 417616130, 'comment_body': 'It could be used for the following documentation problems:
* Vague; not clear; Incomplete; Misleading; Outdated API documentation
* Any spelling mistake
* Any update in dataset description, `home_url`, `citation`, etc.

In my opinion, the above problems could be labeled as `documentation` issue. This will also help us to filter the real bugs.
Or as you suggested we could add a new `other` issue template.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 4, 29, 21, 14, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vijayphoenix', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 417691586, 'comment_body': "Ok sounds good.
